<div data-cms-widget="widgets/Html/Html" id="cms-widget-1c2c00de-9f9e-41e6-8dad-6a04f19ceaea" class="update-center__post">
            <p>April 13, 2020</p>

<p><br>
Chelsea School District Families, </p>

<p>I hope this communication finds you and your families healthy and well.  Since the Governor’s Executive Order 35-2020 to shut down school buildings for the remainder of the school year, we have been addressing the requirements in the Executive Order, navigating the continuous barrage of questions, and sifting through the legal implications that have and will continue as a result.  A requirement of the Executive Order for school districts was the development of a Continuity of Learning Plan. This plan must be approved by the Washtenaw Intermediate School District. Staff members have been working hard to collaborate on this document and develop the plan. The District submitted the COL Plan on Monday, April 13 for approval.  Once it is approved, our staff will organize around its implementation with full implementation scheduled for April 20. In the meantime, our teachers will take part in professional development to adjust to remote learning,  continue to provide enrichment opportunities and connect with students. </p>

<p>Recognizing the individual circumstances of our students and staff has been at the center of the development of the plan.  We understand that everyone’s circumstance is different.  Some of our teachers have their own children at home, are taking care of elderly parents, or have other circumstances that make the transition to remote learning a real challenge.  Our students and families have a variety of circumstances that may prevent them from fully engaging in the content provided.  Some will not be able to engage at all.  </p>

<p>Balancing the academic and social and emotional focus will be imperative as we work through our new reality.  We will continue to calibrate this effort based upon student, staff, and parent feedback.  Please know we are all navigating this together.  It is not going to be perfect, but please know we are all working hard to address the needs of all of our 2,400 students.</p>

<p><strong>Building Entry: </strong><br>
We know that some students still have items such as instruments, medication, and personal items at the schools. We are working on plans for families to retrieve these items that does not endanger the health and safety of staff and families.  More information will be forthcoming.</p>

<h3><strong>Most Common Feedback and Questions from the Survey</strong></h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Equitable access for all students</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>This is a concern.  The COL Plan has provided an outline of support for students to access the learning content in a variety of ways to meet their needs.  This includes on-line, downloadable, and paper copies of content.  Our teachers will continue to collect the data on what our students need in order to access the content and we will find creative ways to meet these needs.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Lack of Internet access or enough to accommodate a family all working from home</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>The District has installed wireless access points on the outside of all of our school buildings.  We are happy to see that some of you are taking advantage of this Internet source.  In addition, we have identified areas in our community that lack good Internet access and will be parking a Chelsea school bus with a hotspot jetpack to provide additional access.  These locations are listed below:</p>

<h3><a href="https://www.chelsea.k12.mi.us/info-tech/wifi-access-maps" target="_blank"><strong>Bus Locations with Wireless Hotspots</strong></a></h3>

<p> </p>

<p>Additionally, The Chelsea Community Foundation has generously donated funds to the District to purchase several more jetpack devices to deploy to areas in need.  These are currently on order.  </p>

<p>Downloadable packets can be accessed by driving to one of the access points and paper packets will be available to families who need them, as well.</p>

<p><strong>Additional Resource:    <u><a href="https://www.internetessentials.com/" target="_blank">Comcast</a></u></strong></p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Will my student move on to the next grade? What about academic and social regression?</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>All students will move on to the next grade in the fall unless retention was discussed with parents prior to the closure.  We understand that some competencies will not be met over this time period. Teachers will adjust their instruction through the closure and into the fall to accommodate our students</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>How will my special education student access the curriculum? What support will be provided? </strong></li>
</ul>
<p>Special Education staff have collaborated with general education staff to ensure that learning material made available to students is accessible to all and when needed, is individualized to meet a student's learning needs.  Special education students will have a variety of supports in place to assist them in accessing the curriculum. These may include: modification of the material, virtual learning sessions with special education staff, mailed modified or adapted material and resources when needed.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Concern for students and staff mental health and well being</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>This is at the forefront of our plan.  We understand that our new normal will take a toll on all of us and our students. I encourage you to reach out to your teachers or building principal if you have individual circumstances that may prevent your child from engaging fully in the District COL Plan.  Additionally, please keep a close eye out on your children and if you have concerns, contact your building principal or communicate this with our support specialists i.e. counselors, social workers, psychologists, etc…</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>How much is too much and how much is not enough?</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>This is a concern for us. We want to make sure that we are able to meet the needs of all of our students. This is quite a task with the variety of circumstances that exist.  We will be surveying you to gather feedback so we can calibrate the level of communication, learning experiences, and community building in the plan. This will allow us to make adjustments based on need.  Thank you for your grace as we work through this together.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Will the teachers be using a video-conferencing tool like Zoom to communicate with students?</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>Teachers will be utilizing Zoom for video-conferencing with students.  The District is currently providing training for staff, developing a distance learning agreement for students and families, and preparing to safely use the tool when they are ready.  You will see communication from your building principal and/or classroom teachers for more information on Zoom this week.  You can help by becoming familiar with Zoom and discussing the use of this tool with your students.  If you are unable to use this resource or would prefer that your child not engage in video-conferencing, please communicate this with your classroom teacher/s or building principal/s and we will make accommodations.</p>

<p><em><strong>Message</strong></em><em></em><br>
This new normal is not easy on any of us, but it is our current reality.  As I watch our staff pull together to problem solve, support each other, and stay connected, I am powerfully reminded that The Chelsea School District is second to none. I know that the Chelsea Way phrase is interpreted differently for everyone. Sometimes people think that when this phrase is used it is braggadocious and omnipotent. From the moment I joined the Chelsea team, I felt a sense of care and belonging from the staff and the community.  I have had staff and families reach out to me at times to lend support and care as I navigated my work as the Superintendent of Schools.  Recently, several staff members and parents have sent messages of support and encouragement as we navigate this unparalleled situation.  This is how I view the Chelsea Way.  This community is filled with caring and compassionate people.  This District employs staff who care about one another, our students, and our Chelsea families. The staff in this District are resilient and put their hearts at the center of their work.  This community and school district is different, and while the distance from each other may seem overwhelming, I believe that as we work through this challenge  it will only bring us closer together.  This is The Chelsea Way!</p>

<p>Please take care of yourselves.</p>

<p><br>
Sincerely,<br>
Julie D. Helber, Ed.D<br>
Superintendent</p>

